    <worksheet name='The Debt Composition Shift '>
      <layout-options>
        <title>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>National Total Household Debt</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </title>
        <caption>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>This chart shows how household debt has shifted over time. Residential mortgages remain the largest liability, starting at </run>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>$2.1T</run>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'> in early 2023 and accounting for most household debt. With so much income committed to housing, many households have limited cash flow flexibility.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>The growing credit card and line of credit balances tell a second story: consumers are increasingly relying on short-term borrowing to manage everyday expenses, pushing total household debt above </run>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>$2.6T</run>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run bold='true' fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'>Business Insight:</run>
            <run fontcolor='#000000' fontname='Benton Sans Book'> As mortgage growth slows, the opportunity shifts from new lending to customer retention and debt restructuring. Banks can identify customers with rising unsecured debt and proactively offer debt consolidation or HELOC solutions before mortgage renewals create additional financial pressure.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </caption>
      </layout-options>
